# 四、Band 8 改写版（建议精读）

---

## Band 8 Version

Advertising has become deeply embedded in modern society. While some people believe that advertisements are highly effective in influencing consumers’ purchasing decisions, others argue that people have become so overwhelmed by advertising that they tend to ignore it. In my opinion, although individuals may overlook certain advertisements, advertising continues to exert a significant influence on consumer behaviour.

On the one hand, it is understandable why some people believe advertising is becoming less effective. Nowadays, people are constantly bombarded with advertisements through television, social media, websites, and public transport. As a result, many consumers have become largely indifferent to them and pay little attention. Moreover, some advertisements are overly repetitive or even misleading, which undermines their credibility. For instance, many internet users skip online advertisements or install ad-blocking software to avoid them altogether.

On the other hand, advertising still plays a crucial role in shaping purchasing decisions. Effective advertisements not only provide information about products but also appeal to consumers on an emotional level through attractive imagery, memorable slogans, and celebrity endorsements. Furthermore, modern advertising has become increasingly personalised thanks to advances in data analytics and artificial intelligence, allowing companies to target highly specific consumer groups with remarkable precision. For example, advertisements displayed on social media platforms are often based on users’ interests and browsing history, making them far more persuasive than traditional forms of advertising.

In conclusion, although some advertisements may be ignored due to overexposure, advertising remains a highly influential force, particularly when it is creative, emotionally engaging, and carefully targeted at consumers.

